website_content.content: Yes, it‚Äôs time once more to look at the convoluted and unusual tale of a real-life, supposed modern-day plesiosaur carcass‚Ä¶ Caption: it‚Äôs 1937, and this long, slender object - apparently the carcass of a peculiar vertebrate animal - has been extracted from the stomach of a Sperm whale at a British Columbian whaling station‚Ä¶ (images from Bousfield & LeBlond 1995). Long-time readers of TetZoo ‚Äì those who remember or read things from versions 2 (the ScienceBlogs years) and 3 (the SciAm years) ‚Äì may remember the several articles there devoted to Cadborosaurus, the supposed sea monster of the British Columbian coast. Partly because those articles have been corrupted or paywalled by their hosters, I figured it‚Äôs time to republish the better part of my Cadborosaurus thoughts here at tetzoo.com. Plus I‚Äôve just produced some quantity of text on the subject for one my TetZoocryptomegathreads at Twitter. Ok‚Ä¶ Cadborosaurus: the background. European colonists of coastal British Columbia, Canada and Washington, USA claimed ‚Äì from the 1880s onwards* ‚Äì to witness a large sea monster in the region‚Äôs coastal waters. Sometimes said to have a head shaped like that of a camel or horse, sometimes said to be hump-backed or serpentine, and sometimes said to be furry or hairy, or scaly, or wrinkled, it became associated in particular with British Columbia‚Äôs Cadboro Bay. In 1933, editor and journalist Archie H. Wills at the Victoria Daily Times adopted the name Cadborosaurus for this mystery sea creature, a moniker first suggested in a letter written to the Victoria Daily Times by I. Vacedun in 1933. * A possible 1791 account was also accepted by some researchers (LeBlond 2001).
